Master Product Requirements Document (PRD)
Product: I.B.I.S. (Intelligent Battlefield Information System) Document Owner: Scout (Senior Product Strategist) Date: March 2026
1. Executive Summary & Product Vision
I.B.I.S. is a B2B2C marketplace and operational ecosystem designed to eliminate administrative friction in live-action airsoft events, ultimately scaling into a tech-facilitated live-action game engine.
The Root Cause (The "Bleeding-Neck" Problem): Contextual whiplash and administrative drag. The transition from ticket purchase to game execution is broken, causing severe delays on game day, breaking player immersion, and burning out staff.
The "Why Now?": The maturation of agentic AI development, edge computing, and backend-as-a-service (BaaS) allows a lean team to build real-time, offline-capable, hierarchical data syncing affordably.
The Unfair Advantage (Distribution): Forced adoption via a "Bowling Pin" GTM strategy. By solving the producer's most painful bottleneck (Saturday morning check-ins), producers will mandate player app downloads, resulting in a $0 Customer Acquisition Cost (CAC).
2. Market Strategy & Viability
Cagan's Four Big Risks Audit
Value Risk (Low): Producers will pay to solve check-in bottlenecks. Players will adopt what is mandated to play.
Usability Risk (Medium/High): Using a phone during a simulated firefight requires dead-simple, high-contrast, glove-friendly UI.
Feasibility Risk (Medium): De-risked by deferring the hardest tech (live geospatial tracking/syncing) to Phase 3, allowing the team to nail the database architecture first.
Business Viability (Low/Medium): The B2B2C and contextual commerce models drastically increase Revenue Per User, validating the TAM.
SWOT Analysis
Strengths: Deep understanding of airsoft mechanics; holistic ecosystem vision; strong contextual commerce integration.
Weaknesses: High initial engineering scope (rostering hierarchy + ticketing); reliance on user hardware in outdoor environments.
Opportunities: Expansion into adjacent live-action markets (mil-sim, paintball); monopolizing the airsoft gear affiliate space.
Threats: Dead cell zones at rural event sites; phone battery drain during 8-hour events.
